    "body": "### Problem\n\n`nvim_get_hl(<ns>, { name = 'Foo' })` creates a cleared highlight group `hl-Foo` if `hl-Foo` does not exist, which is an undocumented side effect.\r\n\r\nThis affects regions highlighted by non-existing highlight groups in a winbar: consider a winbar set to `%#Foo#abcd%*`, if `hl-Foo` does not exist, highlight of `abcd` will fall back to `hl-WinBar` or `hl-WinBarNC`, however if `hl-Foo` is a cleared highlight group, the color of `abcd` will fall back to `hl-Normal`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. nvim --clean\r\n2. `:echo hlexists('Foo')` --> 0\r\n3. `:call nvim_get_hl(0, { 'name' = 'Foo' })`\r\n4. `:echo hlexists('Foo')` --> 1\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n1. nvim --clean\r\n2. `:echo hlexists('Foo')` --> 0\r\n3. `:call nvim_get_hl(0, { 'name' = 'Foo' })`\r\n4. `:echo hlexists('Foo')` --> 0\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.10.0-dev-751+gd086bc1e85\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim does not have `nvim_get_hl()`\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux 6.1.39-2-lts\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm 20230709-182848-f901dfbf\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nAUR",
